content:
My advice here is not to try and judge it in the moment. Let them get the vocal as they hear it and keep all the takes. When you comp later, make your creative decisions and have that conversation then. 

The two reasons are 1. You don't stop the flow. 2. It's so hard to judge in the moment.

@BatMeckley probably has good thoughts on this too

I’m a huge NIN fan, and I had a similar experience this weekend. I’ve seen them four times before, and the sound was always top-notch, but last Saturday they played at some lame festival in Madrid with a 100 dB limit imposed by the city council that totally ruined the show for me. The crowd was almost louder than the band, and while you could hear the mix (more or less), it was impossible to feel it, even though I was in a good spot (centered and close to FOH).

@chrissorem and anyone else who does live sound, I’m curious — what’s your take on SPL levels at rock/electronic gigs?

Personally, I’d rather wear earplugs and still feel that punch in the gut than listen to NIN at 95 dB…
